What makes some languages more difficult to learn than others?¶

by Lauren Marar¶

What linguistic features make some languages harder to learn than others? This analysis will look at langauge difficulty for native English speakers and examine the linguistic features that distinguish easer and more difficult languages. (Note languages will be referred to as "easier" and "difficult" for short, to represent their relative difficulty for an English speaker. Inherent difficult independent of native language is not explored in this project.)

This analysis will utilize two datasets:

  1. The World Atlas of Language Structures (WALS), which catalogues language features for 2,679 languages: https://www.kaggle.com/rtatman/world-atlas-of-language-structures This data comes in both wide and long format. The long format will be used for the bulk of the analysis but the wide format will be pulled in as well as it contains additional information about the language regions.
  2. Language difficulty ratings as determined by the Foreign Service for 67 frequently studied languages: https://www.state.gov/m/fsi/sls/c78549.htm

features_clean['lang_alias'] = features_clean['Language_name']

As the Foreign Service list did not include standard language codes, I visually mapped the languages whose names did not match the WALS dataset. Only a few languages did not have a one-to-one match. Here was the general decision-making process for matching the languages:

  • Arabic - WALS includes numerous Arabic dialects as well as Modern Standards Arabic. I mapped to Modern Standard and one dialect (Egyptian, as it had the most data and is a widely known dialect).
  • Mongolian - WALS has several Mongolic languages. I mapped to Khalkha, which according to Wikipedia, is the most strongly associted with the country of Mongolia.

Data Exploration¶

1. How much do we know about the linguistic features in the dataset?¶

A look at data completness¶

The WALS dataset is actually a compilation of numerous sources on languages, "gathered from descriptive materials (such as reference grammars) by a team of 55 authors" (https://wals.info/). This means that the individual data sources contributing to the database may each cover a different range of languages, and therefore, we will not have data on all the features for all the languages in the dataset.

Let's get a sense of which features we have the most and least data on, in terms of number of languages with values for the feature. WALS often includes "NONE" as one of the values for a feature, so right now we are looking at whether the feature value is known for a given language, not whether or not the language posesses a certain feature.

As you can see, some features, like the order of the subject/object/verb in a sentence, are well known across many languages. Other features are very niche and cover very few languages, such as the "position of negative morphemes in object0initial laguages".

Most languages within a family have the same difficulty rating. Other than the Indo-European family, only Austronesian, Sino-Tibetan, and Afro-Asiatic span more than one difficulty rating. The category III Indo-European languages comprise primarily the "Indo" part of the family, in other words, the South-Central Dravidian and Indic languages of South Asia.

Occurance of linguistic features by language difficulty¶

The following section is the exploratory phase of the heart of the question. It will systematically break down linguistic features by language difficulty to look for features that tend to be more prominent in either easier or harder languages.

As we saw above, the number of languages in each difficulty category vary greatly, with category III highly overrepresented. For an even comparison, we need to calculate the relative frequency of linguistic features accross language difficulty.

The relative frequency of linguistic features by language difficulty¶

With 67 languages and 144 linguistic features, it would be difficult to visualize the relationship between all of the languages and features in one chart. Therefore, I've broken down the features into meaningful clusters:

  • IDs 1-11, 18-19: Consonants and vowels
  • ID 12: Syllable Structure
  • ID 13: Tone
  • IDs 14-17: Stress and rhythm
  • IDs 20-26: Inflection and marking
  • ID 27: Reduplication
  • IDs 28-29: Syncretism
  • IDs 30-32: Gender
  • IDs 33-36: Plurality
  • IDs 37-38: Definite and indefinite articles
  • IDs 39-48, 136-137: Inclusive/exclusive distinction, pronouns and marking
  • IDs 49-52: Case and comitatives/instrumentals
  • IDs 53-56, 131: Numerals and Quantifiers
  • IDs 57-59: Possessives
  • IDs 60-61: Adjectives
  • IDs 61-64: Nouns
  • IDs 65-80: Tense and aspect (and suppletion)
  • IDs 81-89: Sentence structure and order
  • ID 90: Relative clauses
  • IDs 91-97: More order
  • IDs 98-100: Alignment
  • IDs 101-104: Subject and person markers
  • IDs 105-111: Constructions (active, passive, reciprocal etc.)
  • IDs 112-115, 143: Negation
  • ID 116: Polar questions
  • IDs 117-120: Predication
  • IDs 121-123: Comparative constructions and relativization
  • ID 124: 'Want' complement subjects
  • IDs 125-128: Clauses
  • IDs 129-130, 132-135: Vocabulary
  • IDs 138-141: These features will not be analyzed as they apply to very few languages
  • ID 142: Para-linguistic usage of clicks
  • ID 144: Position of negation

Below is a systematic exploration of the relative frequency of the above categories:

Feats 1-11, 18-19: Consonants and Vowels¶

Feats 112-115, 143: Negation

In [400]:
fig=plt.figure(figsize=[10,12])
negation = rel_freq.query('ID_num>=112 & ID_num<=115')
sb.barplot(data=negation,y='feat_val',x='rel_freq',hue='difficulty',palette='viridis_r',alpha=0.85);

Preliminary findings:

  • Much of the world's languages, including all of the category IV languages, always use a predicate negation along with a negative indefinite pronoun such as "nobody". English and other Western European langauges are the few that often do not use this feature.

The "ne" in Russian is an example of predicate negation:

Nikto ne priel.

nobody neg came.

'Nobody came.'

https://wals.info/chapter/115

Feats 117-120: Predication

In [402]:
fig=plt.figure(figsize=[10,7])
predication = rel_freq.query('ID_num>=117 & ID_num<=120')
sb.barplot(data=predication,y='feat_val',x='rel_freq',hue='difficulty',palette='viridis_r',alpha=0.85);

Preliminary Findings:

  • Predication is another feature that is divided geographically. In English, "have/has" is used to indicate possession. Other Western European languages have a similar construction. Conversely, the category III langauges use genetive, topical, and conjunctional possessives. The majority of category IV languages use a locational possessive which translates to something like "to be at" or "to exist". Here is an example in Mongolic:

na-dur morin bui

1sg-at horse be.3sg.pres

I have a horse. (lit. At me is a horse.)

https://wals.info/chapter/117

Feats 121-123: Comparative constructions and relativization

In [403]:

  • English is one of only 12 languages (out of 166) to use relative pronouns to narrow down the someone that is referenced in a sentence (ex. who we met yesterday is used to tell us more about "the person" the sentence "I called the person who we met yesterday". Many of the more difficult languages, particulary East and Southeast Asian languages, use a "gap" strategy by "not using any morphosyntactic (and/or suprasegmental) element".

https://wals.info/chapter/123

Conclusions¶

There are a handful of features that vary according to the difficulty of a language relative to English:

  • Whether the language uses definite articles
  • How the language shows the relationship between participants of an event
  • Whether the language uses prepositions or postpositions
  • Where the language places a relative clause with respect to the noun
  • Where the language places the interrogative phrase in a question
  • How the language aligns a verbal person marker
  • How the language expresses a negative indefinite pronoun
  • How the language forms a yes or no question
  • How the language describes ownership/posession
  • How the language encodes relative clauses

It is possible that some of these features might not actually make a language difficult (such as the absence of definite articles.) Moreover, there may be features not listed above that, when combined with several other features, raise the difficulty of a language. It may be that there are several ways to make a language difficult, by combining a number of unique features, such as that no single feature stands out as the leading cause of language difficulty.

Further research¶

Additional analyses:

  • A regression analysis may better identify if the interaction of multiple features contributes to a language's difficulty.
  • Another challenge was that the frequency of values associated with each linguistic feature were not evenly distributed. Binning values may help discern trends in difficulty. For example, perhaps all easy languages have value a whereas difficult languages may have values b, c, or d. The conclusion may be that the absence of a makes the language more difficult, regardless of whether it is b, c, or d.

Additional data:

  • Because the sample size of very difficult languages was only 5, whereas the other difficulty groups were much larger, it may have made trends harder to spot as the frequency of occurrence in level 5 languages would jump from 40% to 60% with the addition of one language.
  • Furthermore, this analysis does not take into account the number of speakers. While it is difficult to come accross a clean dataset of population by language ID, endeavoring to collect this data would allow us to assess the commonality or rarity of linguistic features by number of speakers, accounting for the fact that languages vary widely by number of native speakers.

In conclusion, it may very well be that those rare category IV languages stem from the perfect storm of a unique set of features, that

Easy languages are all alike; every difficult language is difficult in its own way.
